✦ I've completely changed the approach. The root of the problem is that Git on Windows performs intense filesystem validation checks before creating index entries, and the OS itself rejects the characters when attempting to check them out. Sparse    
  checkout rules unfortunately don't prevent Git from parsing those paths during tree evaluation on checkout.

  I've rewritten that line in install.js to use a bulletproof workaround for Windows:

   1. git clone -n ...: Clones the repo but skips checking out the working directory (leaving it empty).
   2. git config core.protectNTFS false: Disables the strict path validation temporarily.
   3. git reset HEAD: Loads the repository tree into the index (which now succeeds because the strict validation was disabled).
   4. git rm --cached -r assets: Forcibly removes the offending directory (where the files with < and > live) from the Git index.
   5. git checkout .: Checks out everything currently in the index into the working directory (thus completely bypassing the invalid files).
