  You are completely right that torch.js has the correct GPU versions. The problem is that torch.js hasn't run yet when the script tries to install MagiAttention.

  Here is exactly what is happening in install.js right now:
   1. It creates the python environment.
   2. It runs uv pip install -r requirements.txt. Because the environment is empty, this pulls down the default CPU version of PyTorch (2.10.0+cpu).
   3. It tries to build MagiAttention (uv pip install -e MagiAttention). MagiAttention requires compiling CUDA extensions. It checks the environment, sees the CPU version of PyTorch, and immediately fails with the CUDA/NVCC errors you saw.
   4. Only after all of this finishes is torch.js scheduled to run (which would have installed the correct GPU version).

  What I am trying to do:
  I am trying to move the torch.js execution step so that it runs before requirements.txt and MagiAttention are installed.

  By simply swapping the order in install.js, the correct GPU version of PyTorch (from torch.js) will be installed first. Then, when MagiAttention tries to build, it will detect the correct CUDA-enabled PyTorch and compile successfully.
